# Background
Deserializing data without a limit on the types the application will accept has long been a source of remote code execution security vulnerabilities. Some serializers, such as ```DataContractSerializer``` and ```XmlSerializer```, require a list of allowed types, but others, such as ```BinaryFormatter``` do not. While there has long been guidance not to use ```BinaryFormatter``` with untrusted data, both usage and vulnerable applications remain common. These issues are well known and documented enough that there are even [open source tools](https://github.com/pwntester/ysoserial.net) for exploitation. 

Serialization Guard is a proposed mitigation for applications that don't or can't avoid ```BinaryFormatter``` and other non-type-limiting serializers. The intent is to disable known actions during deserialization that are much more likely to be malicious than innocent.

While BinaryFormatter is the most studied .NET serializer for these vulnerabilities, [resarchers showed](https://www.blackhat.com/docs/us-17/thursday/us-17-Munoz-Friday-The-13th-Json-Attacks.pdf) that third-party serializers can be abused as well. By making this API public, we can allow those serializers to participate in Serialization Guard as well.

# Serialization Guard
Deserialization attacks typically involve two parts:
1. Building a "gadget" chain. "Gadgets" are types (usually types in the framework) that do something that can be abused during a deserialization constructor, callback, or property setter. Often, this is a limited, but attacker controlled, usage of reflection (for example, constructing any one object). Usually, the serialization payload must contain a type graph of gadgets in order to achieve sufficient code execution for an attack.
2. Using a "target". While gadgets allow a certain amount of control of the victim process, they're not typically sophisticated enough to run a complete piece of malware. Instead, an attack will generally try to use the gadgets to trigger the next stage of an attack by, for example, loading an assembly from a serialized byte array or by starting a process. While assembly loading and starting processes are not in themselves problematic, they're very suspicious during deserialization. 

Serialization Guard will disable all known gadgets and targets. On .NET Core, there are no known BinaryFormatter gadgets (we didn't make them serializable when we brought BinaryFormatter back), but we may add blocks to future gadgets or gadgets that apply to other serializers over time. The targets we would initially mitigate on .NET Core are Assembly.Load(byte[]), Assembly.Load from an AssemblyName with CodeBase set, Process.Start, and opening a FileStream for write.

# Control of Serialization Guard
Serialization Guard will be controlled by AppContext switches. It will be enabled by default on .NET Core. Individual targets will also have switches so that, for example, a program that intentionally starts a process during deserialization still doesn't have to worry about assemblies loaded from byte arrays. There won't be individual switches for gadgets because they're largely interchangable.

# API
```c#
namespace System.Runtime.Serialization
{
    // Entrypoints are on the SerializationInfo class since it's available to all serializers
    // and can also align with .NET Framework 
    public partial sealed class SerializationInfo
    {
        // Marks a thread as currently undergoing deserialization, meaning that Serialization Guard should kick in
        // Serializers should call this when they begin deserialization before creating any objects.
        // When they're done, they should dispose the DeserializationToken.
        public static DeserializationToken StartDeserialization();

        // True if a DeserializationToken is live on this thread. Can be queried from potential
        // gadgets and targets to see whether to protect themselves
        public static bool DeserializationInProgress { get; }

        // Convenience method for throwing a DangerousDeserializationException if deserialization 
        // is in progress (helpful because that's a pretty common pattern)
        public static void ThrowOnDangerousDeserialization();
    }

    // Used to maintain the state of deserialization being in progress. Once all of these on a thread
    // have been disposed, the thread is no longer deserializing
    public sealed class DeserializationToken : IDisposable
    {
        // No public constructor; these can only be built by SerializationInfo.StartDeserialization()

        public void Dispose();
    }

    // Exception thrown when a dangerous action (gadget or target) tries to run during deserialization.
    // Deriving from SerializationException makes it compatible with many current serializers
    [Serializable]
    public sealed class DangerousDeserializationException : SerializationException
    {
        // Default constructor
        public DangerousDeserializationException();

        // Throws with a message that includes switchName as a way to allow the behavior that's throwing
        public DangerousDeserializationException(string switchName);

        // Useful for unwrapping and rethrowing exceptions (BinaryFormatter will do this)
        public DangerousDeserializationException(Exception innerException);
    }
}
```

# Examples of usage
```c#
[Serializable]
class SomeGadgetType
{
    private SomeGadgetType(SerializationInfo info, StreamingContext context)
    {
        SerializationInfo.ThrowOnDangerousDeserialization();

        // If we got here, Serialization Guard must be disabled. We'll finish deserializing
    }
}
```
```c#
class SomeTargetType
{
    public void DoSomethingPotentiallyDangerous()
    {
        SerializationInfo.ThrowOnDangerousDeserialization();

        // Ok, we're not deseriailzing, we can proceed
    }
}
```

```c#
class SomeCustomSerializer
{
    public object Deserialize(byte[] data)
    {
        using (DeserializationToken token = SerializationInfo.StartDeserialization())
        {
            // Deserialize the data
        }
    }

    // Async works too 
    public async Task<object> DeserializeAsync(Stream dataStream)
    {
        using (DeserializationToken token = SerializationInfo.StartDeserialization())
        {
            byte[] data = new byte[100];
            await dataStream.ReadAsync(data);
            // Deserialize the data
        }
    }
}
```

